#compdef mdbook-epub
# ============================================================================
# mdbook-epub - EPUB renderer for mdbook
#                (Rust, MIT)
#
# Author : Michael F. Bryan (Michael-F-Bryan)
# Upstream: https://github.com/Michael-F-Bryan/mdbook-epub
#
# `mdbook-epub` is an EPUB output backend for
# `mdbook`, the Rust ecosystem's canonical
# markdown-to-book tool used to publish the
# Rust Programming Language Book + the Rust
# Reference + the Rustonomicon + the Cargo
# Book + many other official Rust docs.
#
# Operates in two modes:
#   1. **As an mdbook plugin** (default):
#      reads JSON RenderContext from stdin
#      (mdbook's standard plugin protocol),
#      generates EPUB into the book's build
#      directory
#   2. **Standalone** (--standalone / -s):
#      directly loads book.toml from a
#      filesystem path, builds, and renders
#      to EPUB without going through mdbook
#
# Output:
#   - **EPUB v3** archive containing:
#       * OPF package document (metadata +
#         manifest + spine)
#       * NCX navigation document (legacy
#         compatibility)
#       * Nav HTML document (EPUB3-native
#         navigation)
#       * Chapter HTML files (rendered from
#         markdown via pulldown-cmark)
#       * Embedded images + assets
#       * Embedded CSS (default theme +
#         user-provided)
#
# Distinguishing features vs alternatives:
#   - **Official mdbook plugin protocol**
#     (uses mdbook's RenderContext stdin/
#     JSON contract; works alongside other
#     mdbook backends like html + pdf)
#   - **Standalone mode** for CI workflows
#     that don't want to invoke mdbook
#     directly
#   - **pulldown-cmark backend** (the
#     canonical Rust CommonMark parser;
#     same renderer mdbook itself uses for
#     HTML output - ensures consistent
#     markdown semantics)
#   - **Image + asset embedding** (URLs in
#     markdown are auto-resolved + assets
#     bundled into the EPUB archive via
#     ureq-based fetching)
#   - **MIME detection via infer + mime_
#     guess** (correctly types embedded
#     assets for EPUB v3 manifest)
#
# Use cases:
#   - Generate EPUB versions of mdbook
#     projects for distribution (offline
#     reading + e-reader compatibility)
#   - Self-publishing technical books
#     written in markdown
#   - Convert Rust documentation books to
#     EPUB for tablet/e-reader review
#   - CI pipeline that produces multiple
#     output formats from a single
#     markdown source (HTML + PDF + EPUB
#     via parallel mdbook backends)
#   - Archival format for evolving
#     technical documentation
#
# Usage:
#   mdbook-epub [-s] [<root>]
#
# As an mdbook plugin (default mode),
# invoked by mdbook via book.toml:
#   ```toml
#   [output.epub]
#   ```
# Then `mdbook build` runs html (default) +
# epub backends.
#
# Standalone mode:
#   mdbook-epub -s [path-to-book]
#
# Flags (clap derive):
#   -s, --standalone               - run
#                                     standalone
#                                     (not as
#                                     mdbook
#                                     plugin)
#   [root]                         - root
#                                     folder of
#                                     book to
#                                     render
#                                     (default
#                                     ".")
#   -h, --help                     - show
#                                     help
#   -V, --version                  - show
#                                     version
#
# Example invocations:
#   # Plugin mode: invoked by mdbook
#   mdbook build
#
#   # Standalone mode for a book at path
#   mdbook-epub --standalone /path/to/book
#
#   # Standalone for current directory
#   mdbook-epub -s
#
# Configuration (in book.toml):
#   [output.epub]
#   additional-css = ["custom-epub.css"]
#   cover-image = "cover.png"
#   use-default-css = true
#   curly-quotes = true
#   smart-punctuation = true
#
# The pulldown-cmark lane is built on
# `pulldown-cmark = "0.13.0"` (declared
# verbatim at upstream Cargo.toml HEAD as a
# direct dep, imported by `src/generator.rs`
# for markdown chapter parsing + transformation
# to EPUB-compatible HTML), the canonical
# Rust CommonMark parser by Raph Levien +
# Marcus Klaas + the pulldown-cmark
# maintainer team - github.com/pulldown-
# cmark/pulldown-cmark.
#
# pulldown-cmark/pulldown-cmark is the
# de-facto canonical Rust markdown parser:
#   - **CommonMark spec compliant**
#     (CommonMark v0.30 + GFM extensions)
#   - **Pull-based parser API**
#     (event-stream + zero-allocation;
#     iterators yield events without
#     building a heavy AST)
#   - **GFM extensions** (tables +
#     strikethrough + tasklists +
#     autolinks + footnotes)
#   - **Pure-Rust implementation** (no C
#     dependencies)
#   - **Used by mdbook itself** (and
#     rustdoc's markdown rendering)
#   - **2,400+ stars on github.com/
#     pulldown-cmark/pulldown-cmark**
#   - **~10,000 reverse-deps on
#     crates.io (one of the most-
#     imported Rust libraries)**
#
# pulldown-cmark's distinguishing position
# vs Rust markdown alternatives:
#   - pulldown-cmark/pulldown-cmark (Levien
#     + Klaas + team): canonical;
#     CommonMark v0.30; pull-based; THIS
#     AXIS
#   - markdown-rs (johannhof/markdown-rs):
#     alternative full-AST parser;
#     CommonMark + extensions; broader
#     scope but slower
#   - comrak (kivikakk): port of cmark-gfm
#     (the GitHub Flavored Markdown
#     reference C implementation); used
#     by GitHub-style renderers
#   - md-rs: smaller alternative
#
# Raph Levien is one of the most influential
# figures in the Rust + computer graphics
# communities:
#   - **Original pulldown-cmark author**
#     (started 2015 as an experiment in
#     pull-based parsing)
#   - **xi-editor + Druid creator** (the
#     experimental Rust text editor + GUI
#     framework; many ideas live on in
#     Linebender)
#   - **Linebender founder + Vello
#     compute-shader 2D renderer
#     architect** (the most ambitious Rust
#     2D graphics project; targets wgpu/
#     WebGPU)
#   - **Variable font + font interpolation
#     research** (the Spiro spline + OFL
#     font Inconsolata's original author)
#   - **Google Fonts + Trajan engineer
#     before independent work**
#
# Levien's role in Rust is *foundational
# computing infrastructure across graphics +
# text + parsing*. His libraries are
# influential beyond their direct usage -
# pulldown-cmark's pull-based API design
# influenced parser API design across many
# language ecosystems.
#
# Marcus Klaas is the long-time primary
# maintainer of pulldown-cmark after
# Levien's initial development; managed the
# v0.x release series + spec compliance
# updates.
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Rust author/org
# cohort extension (now spanning even more
# distinct authors):
#   - + Raph Levien + Marcus Klaas +
#     pulldown-cmark org (pulldown-cmark
#     + Linebender Vello + xi-editor;
#     THIS AXIS; canonical Rust
#     CommonMark parser + graphics +
#     text-rendering ecosystem
#     foundational infrastructure)
#
# Levien's joining the canonical-Rust
# cohort at the *cross-domain foundational
# infrastructure* level extends the
# pattern of cross-vertical canonical
# authors. He has canonical presence in:
#   - Markdown parsing (pulldown-cmark)
#   - 2D graphics (Vello + Druid)
#   - Text editing (xi-editor heritage)
#   - Variable fonts (academic + Google
#     Fonts work)
#
# Cross-domain canonical-author presence
# is rare; Levien is one of the few
# documented in the Rust canonical-author
# cohort.
#
# mdbook-epub uses pulldown-cmark for:
#   - Parsing each chapter's markdown
#     source into a stream of CommonMark
#     events
#   - Transforming the event stream to
#     EPUB-compatible HTML (adjusting
#     relative URLs for asset bundling +
#     applying additional CSS classes)
#   - Image URL extraction (for the
#     asset-bundling step that downloads
#     external images + embeds them in
#     the EPUB archive)
#   - GFM extension handling (tables +
#     tasklists + footnotes are common
#     in technical documentation)
#
# This is the canonical use case for
# pulldown-cmark in Rust documentation
# tooling: stream-based markdown parsing
# that allows efficient transformation
# without building a full AST.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 284 :: Markdown / CommonMark parsing
#              libraries
#              (CommonMark v0.30 spec
#              compliant parsers; GFM
#              extension support; AST
#              vs event-stream parsers)
# Round 1550 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 284
#
# Cross-language canonical library family
# for this axis (proposed):
#   Rust    : pulldown-cmark/pulldown-cmark - Raph
#                                            Levien +
#                                            Marcus
#                                            Klaas
#                                            (canonical
#                                            Rust
#                                            CommonMark;
#                                            event-
#                                            stream
#                                            API)
#   Go      : yuin/goldmark              - Yusuke
#                                            Inuzuka
#                                            (canonical
#                                            Go
#                                            CommonMark;
#                                            used by
#                                            Hugo)
#   TS/Node : markedjs/marked            - Christopher
#                                            Jeffrey +
#                                            Tony Brix
#                                            (canonical
#                                            Node
#                                            markdown
#                                            parser;
#                                            ~17M
#                                            weekly
#                                            npm
#                                            downloads)
#
# Markdown is the *most-deployed lightweight
# markup format on the modern web*:
#   - **Originally specified by John Gruber
#     2004** (Daring Fireball blog)
#   - **CommonMark v0.30** at commonmark.org
#     (community standardization effort;
#     unambiguous parsing semantics)
#   - **GFM (GitHub Flavored Markdown)**
#     extensions (tables + tasklists +
#     strikethrough + autolinks +
#     footnotes; widely adopted beyond
#     GitHub)
#
# Each canonical library provides:
#   - CommonMark v0.30 parsing
#   - GFM extension support (varies by
#     library)
#   - HTML rendering (most common output)
#   - Custom renderer interfaces (for
#     non-HTML outputs like EPUB + PDF +
#     LaTeX)
#
# Use-case spectrum for this axis (so far):
#   - mdbook-epub (Rust, pulldown-cmark):
#     EPUB rendering for mdbook
#     technical books + Rust
#     documentation
# ============================================================================

_mdbook-epub() {
    _arguments \
        '(-s --standalone)'{-s,--standalone}'[run standalone (not as mdbook plugin)]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[show version]' \
        '*:book root:_files -/'
}

_mdbook-epub "$@"
